      "note": "Lit., \"two by two (mathna) and singly (furada)\". According to Razi, the expression mathna denotes, in this context, \"together with another person\" or \"other persons\": hence, the above phrase may be understood to refer to man's social behaviour - i.e., his actions concerning others - as well as to his inner, personal attitude in all situations requiring a moral choice."
